It seems that there have been a lot of misconceptions about the rules
about leaving a clan and joining a new one.  For a while, the primary rule
of thumb has been "No, no, no."  However, in practice, a lot of situations
have come up where it made sense for exceptions to be made, and the lines
have been blurred.

In truth, there are situations where it is acceptable for a player to leave
a clan and join another.  Those situations are:
 

1) The clan changes. Example: Analar, an anti-paladin in Shadow, left their
ranks after their doctrine changed to exclude magic users.

2) The clan leader rejects and kicks out a member for one reason or another.
Example: A new leader takes over for a clan, and decides to "clean house," and
remove members he doesn't like or ones who don't support his rule. (Other
clans should think long and hard about accepting someone who's been rejected
from another clan, though.)

3) The player didn't meet the guidelines for the clan when he was accepted.
Example: Someone who was not chaotic found himself in clan Chaos. His
membership is essentially invalid; a mistake. (And whoever let him in will
probably find themselves in some amount of trouble for not being more
thorough and careful.)

In all of the above situations (the first two more than the last), there must
be some sort of PUBLIC ROLEPLAY on the part of both the player leaving the clan
and the clan's leader, and if/when the player finds himself wanting to join
a second clan, there must be EXPLICIT IMMORTAL APPROVAL for their admittance.


If anyone has any questions about this, please feel free to ask.
 
(Help written by Angelo)
 
