1 0 THORNAN BATTLE HUNTING WAR WARRIOR RANGER~
The Lord of Battle is as chaotic in nature as war itself.  He favors a
side almost randomly, smiling on the defender one moment, then the attackers
the next.  This only tends to add to the ebbs and flow of the battle, the
very thing that Thornan loves.  By his very nature however, he is neutral as
to the battle's outcome and so rarely will he act decisively for one side of
the other, rather he may be on one side one day, then against them the next.
For all of this, Thornan is still a warrior and hunter and he will often
smile on great feats of bravery in battle, although of course he might
reward them with a glorious death just as easily as victory.  He hates
cowardice and will vent his displeasure on any that show it during a battle.
Just as Thunder and Lightning over the seas are said to be the anger of the
tempest, when it is seen in the mountains it is said that Thornan is hunting
and that the rumbles are his war chariot, the flashes, the light from his
Axe and Hammer.  Few but the bravest souls will venture from the valley
during such times.  When the night skies are clear and a streak of light is
seen racing cross it, it is said that Thornan hunts the stars themselves,
and that the sparks of light are his arrows.  Thornan is also the hunter's
guide, and Lord of the animals.  Few hunters will take an animal without
giving thanks to Thornan for the bounty and gift he has granted them.  Just
as in battle, he is chaotic in his giving, sometimes on the hunter's side,
and sometimes the prey.  This keeps the balance between the natural life and
those that need to use it to survive.  Thornan makes his home in the forests
and the mountains of Thera.  As the Lord of Battle, Thornan oversees all
battles, be they great or small.  He blesses bravery and shows his
displeasure on cowardice.  He is also the god of hunting and animals,
watching over both and ensuring that there will always be enough prey for
the hunters.  Thornan's symbol is a shield with a hammer or axe embossed
onto it.  This can be any size and so can be worn as a pendant, or as a real
shield.  His color is a blood red, the same as that spilled by warriors and
animals.  His sacared animal is the Lion and his drink is the Ale that is
loved by dwarven warriors.  While Thornan's priests are busiest when there
is a battle coming, they are active at all times of the years.  They have a
number of duties, from blessing hunters and leading celebrations of thanks
for a successful hunt, to joining the front ranks of the army when war is on
the way.  Even during times of peace, the priests of Thornan are easy to
spot.  They either wear blood red armor, which they keep well maintained, or
blood red robes and a steel skullcap.  Most of Thornan's followers are
warriors and hunters, sometimes both, such as the scouts and rangers who
wander the hills and valley.  Though monetary offerings are very much
acceptable by the temples, many given their offerings in way of meat taken
on a hunt or weapons and armor that they have crafted.  During war times,
the numbers of people who come to the temple increase vastly as they pray to
Thornan to smile on loved ones involved in the fighting and for their side
to have a quick and decisive victory.  While Thornan is remembered on many
days of the year, playing an under card role on Zsuzsu's Day of Remembrance,
the first of the year and having prayers and feasts held by veterans on the
anniversaries of great battles, his main day is the last day of the year,
the claimed day of the finding of the valley and city.  On this day all
people remember the wars and battles of the past as well as those lives that
have been lost.  At dawn, soldiers, retired and active, march in full armor
through the city to the city center (market square), each company carrying a
reef of flowers to place on the memorial there.  Once the prayers and
speeches are done, there is a celebration, which is held to celebrate the
victories won and those comrades in arms who have passed on.  Unlike the Day
of Remembrance, Victory Day is held with reverence, but also celebration and
joy.  
